# 25_pnl_styles_smoke — first panel-as-Scriptable smoke test (s202 m1).
#
# Exercises the verbs and queries the `pnl_styles` companion publishes:
#
#   verbs:    new_style, expand_category, highlight_self
#   queries:  active_category, active_is_app_tier
#
# Per CANON's "The script has no fingers": this test never reaches
# for a panel handle, never uses the `do <action.name>` shape that
# s201 m3 introduced. It addresses `pnl_styles` directly, the way a
# real user would address the kebab — by name, with verbs that
# describe outcomes the user can perform. The Scriptable's
# implementation reaches the panel's private surface via the
# friend declaration; the script side never sees that boundary.
#
# This is the symmetric finish of test 24's s201 m3 self-driving
# refactor. After m2 lands, test 24 can switch its prologue from
# `do styles.create-empty` to `pnl_styles new_style` and gain the
# narrated kebab dance for free.
#
# Test protocol — FULLY SELF-DRIVING:
#
#   1. Open Curvz with a fresh / default document.
#   2. Open the Scripter window.
#   3. Load this script.
#   4. Run. The script flashes the panel, walks the active-category
#      state, opens the Style Editor via the Scriptable, then closes
#      it via the dialog's existing substrate Cancel button.
#
# On the panel's initial state (fresh-project version, post m1 fix):
#
# StylesPanel always shows exactly one category — there's no "nothing
# selected" state. The dropdown chooser orders categories app-tier
# first, then user "(uncategorised)" if any user styles exist there,
# then named user categories alphabetically. On a fresh project the
# only category is the app-tier "Built-in" bucket, so the panel opens
# there and active_is_app_tier is true. As the user creates styles
# the picture grows; this test asserts only the pieces that hold on
# every fresh open.

#[sub] Initial state — fresh project lands on the "Built-in" app-tier
#[sub] bucket. StylesPanel always shows one category at a time; with
#[sub] no user styles yet there's nothing else for it to land on.

assert pnl_styles active_category == "Built-in"
assert pnl_styles active_is_app_tier == true

#[sub] s202 m4 — section state. The Styles inspector section opens
#[sub] collapsed by default (make_section's expanded=false in
#[sub] MainWindow_zones), though the user may have opened it before
#[sub] running this script. Force it closed first so the round-trip
#[sub] asserts have a defined starting state, then expand and verify.
#[sub] expand_section invokes the apply-state closure MainWindow
#[sub] handed the panel — the same path the user-driven header
#[sub] click takes, so the body becomes visible, the arrow flips
#[sub] to ▾, and the project's sec_styles_open flag updates. This
#[sub] is the required pre-condition for show_kebab and highlight_self
#[sub] below: a collapsed section means widgets inside have no
#[sub] on-screen allocation, so popovers fall back to default
#[sub] locations and CSS-class flashes paint on invisible widgets.

pnl_styles collapse_section
assert pnl_styles section_open == false
pnl_styles expand_section
assert pnl_styles section_open == true

#[sub] s202 m5 — composite focus_section. Distinct from the narrow
#[sub] expand_section above: focus_section collapses every registered
#[sub] inspector section first, then walks the ancestor chain open.
#[sub] For Styles that means "Content" group opens too, not just
#[sub] the leaf section. The post-condition assert verifies the
#[sub] Styles section is open after the focus move; the cascade of
#[sub] other sections collapsing is visible to the viewer but not
#[sub] easily asserted from the pnl_styles surface (each panel's
#[sub] section_open lives on its own Scriptable). The user-facing
#[sub] outcome is "inspector quiets, ancestor chain opens" — the
#[sub] right starting state for a narrated walkthrough.

pnl_styles focus_section
assert pnl_styles section_open == true
sleep 400

#[sub] highlight_self — pulse the panel root so the viewer's eye
#[sub] lands on the styles section before anything else happens.
#[sub] The CSS class .demo-highlight tints the background and draws
#[sub] an accent outline; it auto-removes after 600ms (default) so
#[sub] subsequent narration doesn't carry a stale highlight.

pnl_styles highlight_self
sleep 700

#[sub] highlight_self with a custom duration argument — 300ms.
#[sub] Optional int arg; default 600 if omitted, negative or zero
#[sub] silently falls back to the default.

pnl_styles highlight_self 300
sleep 400

#[sub] expand_category "Built-in" — round-trip on a name we know
#[sub] exists. The Scriptable walks m_category_order to resolve the
#[sub] tier automatically; calling set_active_category directly
#[sub] would have required the script to know "Built-in" is app-
#[sub] tier. The post-condition assert proves the switch happened
#[sub] AND that the tier resolution worked.

pnl_styles expand_category "Built-in"
assert pnl_styles active_category == "Built-in"
assert pnl_styles active_is_app_tier == true

#[sub] expand_category on a name that doesn't exist — silent no-op.
#[sub] The Scriptable's intent is "go there if it exists," so a miss
#[sub] keeps the panel where it was rather than falling back to some
#[sub] unrelated category. The post-condition assert proves the
#[sub] panel didn't move.

pnl_styles expand_category "Nonexistent Category"
assert pnl_styles active_category == "Built-in"

#[sub] m2 kebab dance — show_kebab opens the popover programmatically,
#[sub] kebab_visible query reads the MenuButton's :active property to
#[sub] confirm. highlight_menuitem walks the popover's child tree to
#[sub] find the model button whose action-name is "styles.create-empty"
#[sub] and pulses it with .demo-highlight for 600ms. hide_kebab dismisses
#[sub] the popover and proactively cancels the highlight (the popover
#[sub] destroys its model-button children on hide, so the highlight
#[sub] timeout's lambda would dangle without the cancel).

assert pnl_styles kebab_visible == false
pnl_styles show_kebab
sleep 400
assert pnl_styles kebab_visible == true

pnl_styles highlight_menuitem "create-empty"
sleep 600

pnl_styles hide_kebab
sleep 200
assert pnl_styles kebab_visible == false

#[sub] new_style — invoke the panel's "+ New style" outcome through
#[sub] the registered Scriptable. Identical end-state to `do
#[sub] styles.create-empty` from test 24, but the script side now
#[sub] addresses an outcome by name on a registered object instead
#[sub] of dispatching a Gio action by string. The Style Editor
#[sub] dialog appears non-modal; the script retains focus.

pnl_styles new_style
sleep 200

#[sub] The dialog's substrate widgets are now registered (StyleEditorDialog
#[sub] singleton lifetime, s201 m1). Round-trip one widget to prove the
#[sub] dialog is alive and addressable, then close.

assert dlg_se_cnc label == "Cancel"
dlg_se_cnc click

#[sub] s202 m4 — clean up by re-collapsing the section. The test
#[sub] expanded it explicitly at the start; leaving it open across
#[sub] runs would mean a second run sees a different initial state.
#[sub] collapse_section is symmetric with expand_section and idempotent
#[sub] (no-op if already closed).

pnl_styles collapse_section
assert pnl_styles section_open == false

#[sub] Done. If every line PASSed, the panel-as-Scriptable foundation
#[sub] is sound. Every new_style / expand_category / highlight_self /
#[sub] show_kebab / highlight_menuitem / hide_kebab / expand_section /
#[sub] collapse_section / focus_section verb went through the
#[sub] Scriptable's invoke() dispatch and the friend-reach into
#[sub] StylesPanel — no accessor leak, no `do` verb, no Gio-action
#[sub] string from the script side.
